{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"095fbe09-ec64-45d3-8069-ee79992bcdc0","content":"You can download the **standalone version** of `dotnet-trace` directly — no SDK required. Inside the container, run:\n\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\nThen collect a CPU trace:\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n/tmp/dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a trace (cpu-sampling is the default profile)\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\n**Key notes:**\n- Use `linux-arm64` instead of `linux-x64` if on ARM.\n- The output `.nettrace` file can be viewed in **PerfView** (Windows) or converted to Speedscope JSON with `dotnet-trace convert`.\n- Add `--duration 00:00:30` to auto-stop after 30 seconds.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"42fc6680-0ccc-4c0e-b05b-ca58aa20352a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a .NET container that doesn't have the SDK installed. This is a common operational question about .NET diagnostics tooling. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.\n\nThe standard approach is to use `dotnet-tool install` but that requires the SDK. For containers without the SDK, you can download the standalone tool directly.\n\nMicrosoft publishes standalone builds of dotnet-trace (and other diagnostic tools) that don't require the SDK. You can download them directly via their CDN.\n\nLet me give a clear, concise answer.","outputTokens":376,"requestId":"AC10:210854:14953A8:17057A2:6A06715A"},"id":"f63d9125-07a6-41fc-a352-5120dbb87e47","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:05:39.792Z","parentId":"e1465532-825a-46b8-965a-1bbe33f8b36d"}
